15 things you should know before visiting Santorini 🩵🤍

1. Oia isn’t the only pretty town 🇬🇷 Imerovigli and some other villages are quieter and just as stunning.
2. Sunsets in Oia are chaotic 🌅 Go to a rooftop restaurant or Imerovigli for a more relaxed view. Also booking a suite with the sunset view might be a good idea.
3. Book transfers in advance. Taxis are limited and can get very expensive. Renting a car is also convenient.
4. Wear comfortable shoes! The streets are cobbled, steep, and unforgiving in heels. 
5. It gets windy 💨 Pack a light jacket, even in summer. Also the nights might be cooler as the wind starts at the sunset.
6. You don’t need to stay in Oia. There are amazing hotels with caldera views all over the island.
7. Many hotels aren’t accessible. Lots of stairs, so double-check in advance!!
8. Caldera view > beach view 🩵 Santorini is about cliffs and volcano views.
9. Book dinner spots early. Sunset-view restaurants fill up weeks in advance.
10. It’s not cheap – Santorini is luxury-priced, even for simple meals in the most popular areas.
11. There is an amazing winery scene. Don’t miss the local Assyrtiko wine. Having a wine tasting is an amazing idea 🍇
12. Private terraces aren’t always private. Some are visible to other guests because of the hills.
13. The airport is tiny and chaotic. Be patient.
14. You don’t need to see everything. Santorini is best enjoyed slowly, with wine and a view by the pool.
15. Stay more than 3 nights. Many say that you can see the island in only a couple days but I disagree. There is so many things to see and do and the views are amazing for just relaxing by the pool.

Higgen gem of Costa Blanca 🌞

In the mountains of Alicante, Guadalest is one of Spain’s most beautiful villages. This tiny hilltop town with under 300 residents is famous for its medieval castle, turquoise water, and charming streets filled with local shops and cafés. It’s a must-visit if you’re exploring Costa Blanca! ✨

15 things I wish I knew before visiting thw South of France 🌞🇫🇷

1. Nice is the perfect base: Well-connected, lively, and relatively affordable.

2. The beaches are pebbly: Not the soft sand you might expect, but still beautiful.

3. Public transport is amazing: You can train-hop to Cannes, Antibes, Villefranche-sur-Mer, Eze & Monaco easily.

4. Old towns are the real deal: Explore the pastel alleyways in Antibes, Menton, and Villefranche.

5. Eze isn’t just a photo stop: It’s one of the prettiest villages in France, with stunning views and amazing restaurants.

6. Cannes isn’t just about the festival: Great shopping, beaches, and a beautiful old town too.

7. Don’t skip Menton: It’s 100% worth the distance.

8. Beach clubs are pricey: But worth it for the comfort, views and atmosphere.

9. Reserve restaurants early: Seaside tables and sunset spots book out fast in high season.

10. Reserve beach clubs early too: The best ones are booked up days (or weeks) ahead in summer.

11. Charming inland villages exist too: Try Saint-Paul-de-Vence for art and hilltop views.

12. Traffic to Saint-Tropez is no joke: Leave early or consider arriving by boat.

13. There’s no Uber in Monaco: Plan ahead or use local taxis (they can be pricey and in high demand).

14. Don’t overplan: The French Riviera is made for long lunches, slow strolls and days by the beach.

15. You will definitely dream of coming back 🥹✨
